If, then, instruction is the 
real thing that separates

54
00:02:37,923 --> 00:02:40,492
a computer from 
a straightforward calculator.

55
00:02:40,525 --> 00:02:43,395
It can make little decisions 
within itself.

56
00:02:43,428 --> 00:02:45,063
(instructor) 
It is the program 
that is the key

57
00:02:45,097 --> 00:02:48,333
to the computer's 
effectiveness and versatility.

58
00:02:48,367 --> 00:02:52,504
Through the program, man 
communicates with the machine.

59
00:02:55,374 --> 00:02:56,942
Ha ha! 
Coding's magic.

60
00:02:56,975 --> 00:02:59,111
Coding is behind everything.

61
00:02:59,144 --> 00:03:00,846
Your pocket is full of code.

62
00:03:00,879 --> 00:03:02,547
It's got your phone in it.

63
00:03:02,581 --> 00:03:04,416
And so it's really like--

64
00:03:04,449 --> 00:03:05,817
coders should be 
everybody at this point.

65
00:03:05,851 --> 00:03:07,786
There's so many exciting 
things that you can do.

66
00:03:07,819 --> 00:03:09,655
You can make music, 
you can do fashion,

67
00:03:09,688 --> 00:03:12,391
you can do all kinds 
of things with code.

68
00:03:12,424 --> 00:03:15,060
We're kind of on the precipice 
of everyone being a coder.

69
00:03:16,728 --> 00:03:19,531
Basically it's writing 
a set of instructions,

70
00:03:19,564 --> 00:03:23,568
and those instructions 
are what a computer follows.

71
00:03:23,602 --> 00:03:26,938
You put all those together 
and you have e-mail,

72
00:03:26,972 --> 00:03:28,874
and you have iTunes,

73
00:03:28,907 --> 00:03:31,376
and you have 
all kinds of cool things.

74
00:03:32,544 --> 00:03:34,846
Regardless of if you want 
a job in this field or not,

75
00:03:34,880 --> 00:03:36,381
I think learning something 
about computer science

76
00:03:36,415 --> 00:03:37,716
is pretty important.

77
00:03:37,749 --> 00:03:39,084
I think it's 
an important life skill.

78
00:03:39,117 --> 00:03:40,786
In the same way 
that everyone should know

79
00:03:40,819 --> 00:03:42,654
a little bit about law, 
and everyone should know

80
00:03:42,688 --> 00:03:44,523
a little bit about economics, 
you probably should know

81
00:03:44,556 --> 00:03:46,658
a little bit about 
computer science.

82
00:03:46,692 --> 00:03:49,127
Everything from your 
navigation system in your car

83
00:03:49,161 --> 00:03:52,030
to the way we think 
about credit card fraud,

84
00:03:52,064 --> 00:03:54,833
it's all radically changed 
behind the scenes.

85
00:03:54,866 --> 00:03:56,168
(female computer voice) 
Enter your passcode.

86
00:03:56,201 --> 00:03:58,103
There's no one way 
to do coding.

87
00:03:58,136 --> 00:04:02,007
It's about problem solving 
in a very precise way,

88
00:04:02,040 --> 00:04:04,676
but also in a creative way.

89
00:04:04,710 --> 00:04:05,911
You can write some code once,

90
00:04:05,944 --> 00:04:08,780
hundreds of millions of people 
or more can be accessing

91
00:04:08,814 --> 00:04:10,415
the products that you've built.

92
00:04:10,449 --> 00:04:11,883
(female computer voice) 
Yelp. Yelp.

93
00:04:11,917 --> 00:04:14,119
(Danielle Feinberg) 
You can combine code 
with anything you love

94
00:04:14,152 --> 00:04:15,821
and you can have a job doing it.

95
00:04:15,854 --> 00:04:19,591
I loved art and I loved coding 
and now I get to make movies.

96
00:04:23,695 --> 00:04:25,630
So if you take 
our film, "Brave,"

97
00:04:25,664 --> 00:04:26,965
and our main character, Merida,

98
00:04:26,998 --> 00:04:29,534
and she's got this 
huge head of red hair.

99
00:04:29,568 --> 00:04:33,638
And to make those curls 
move the right way,

100
00:04:33,672 --> 00:04:35,674
you have to consider 
the physics of things.

101
00:04:35,707 --> 00:04:37,576
There's so many 
different algorithms,

102
00:04:37,609 --> 00:04:40,479
like thousands of them, 
that we use all the time.

103
00:04:40,512 --> 00:04:44,216
And then you code 
up those equations.

104
00:04:44,249 --> 00:04:46,184
And then for all 
the shots in the movie,

105
00:04:46,218 --> 00:04:47,385
the code crunches the numbers

106
00:04:47,419 --> 00:04:50,489
and takes into account 
things like wind, and gravity,

107
00:04:50,522 --> 00:04:53,058
and whether Merida's climbing 
a mountain, or riding a horse,

108
00:04:53,091 --> 00:04:59,598
and does it brush her shoulder, and all of these things.

109
00:04:59,631 --> 00:05:01,733
So, what you get 
is this lovely teenager

110
00:05:01,767 --> 00:05:03,068
that's fiery and spirited,

111
00:05:03,101 --> 00:05:04,803
and it sort of 
sells her personality

112
00:05:04,836 --> 00:05:06,872
and her hair moves 
the right way.

113
00:05:06,905 --> 00:05:11,810
I am Merida and I'll be 
shooting for my own hand.

114
00:05:13,645 --> 00:05:16,047
What are you doing?

115
00:05:16,615 --> 00:05:18,784
I've worked at Pixar 
for 17 years.

116
00:05:18,817 --> 00:05:21,119
I have a computer science degree 
from Harvard,

117
00:05:21,153 --> 00:05:23,054
but had always 
done a lot of art,

118
00:05:23,088 --> 00:05:26,925
and so kind of worked my way 
from technical into creative.

119
00:05:26,958 --> 00:05:29,628
For me, being a teenager, 
I think of it as sort of

120
00:05:29,661 --> 00:05:32,097
one foot being in the world 
of being a kid

121
00:05:32,130 --> 00:05:34,099
and one foot in the world 
of being an adult,

122
00:05:34,132 --> 00:05:36,101
and figuring out who you 
are away from your family,

123
00:05:36,134 --> 00:05:37,636
and sort of 
coming into your own,

124
00:05:37,669 --> 00:05:39,004
what's your voice, 
all of these things.

125
00:05:40,238 --> 00:05:42,841
- Merida! 
- Curse this dress!

126
00:05:42,941 --> 00:05:44,476
[fabric ripping]

127
00:05:45,210 --> 00:05:46,745
[crowd gasping]

128
00:05:46,778 --> 00:05:48,713
Merida, stop this!

129
00:05:49,781 --> 00:05:51,850
(Danielle Feinberg) 
So this idea of Merida 
as this teenager

130
00:05:51,883 --> 00:05:54,019
and she's trying to 
find her way in the world,

131
00:05:54,052 --> 00:05:57,889
brought me to this time period 
in my life in 8th grade.

132
00:05:57,923 --> 00:06:00,192
There's this class and 
it's called Power Mechanics.

133
00:06:00,225 --> 00:06:02,828
And the idea was that 
you take a lawnmower

134
00:06:02,861 --> 00:06:05,030
that's been donated to 
the local hardware store

135
00:06:05,063 --> 00:06:06,965
that doesn't work anymore, 
and you take it apart,

136
00:06:06,998 --> 00:06:09,668
and you put it back together 
with the idea that at the end,

137
00:06:09,701 --> 00:06:11,803
maybe it would work, 
hopefully.

138
00:06:11,837 --> 00:06:13,305
I was definitely 
the only girl in there,

139
00:06:13,338 --> 00:06:15,841
but it wasn't like I turned into the school pariah or anything,

140
00:06:15,874 --> 00:06:17,142
so it was okay.

141
00:06:17,175 --> 00:06:19,711
At the end of the semester, 
we rolled the lawnmowers out,

142
00:06:19,744 --> 00:06:21,880
and I just happened to be 
the last one in line.

143
00:06:21,913 --> 00:06:23,748
And so I'm watching 
as these guys are pulling

144
00:06:23,782 --> 00:06:26,017
the string on the lawnmower, 
and nothing's happening,

145
00:06:26,051 --> 00:06:28,186
and it's silent except 
for all of this, sort of like,

146
00:06:28,220 --> 00:06:29,354
frustration going on.

147
00:06:29,387 --> 00:06:32,824
The teacher finally gets to me 
and puts the gas in,

148
00:06:32,858 --> 00:06:34,159
and I take this deep breath,

149
00:06:34,192 --> 00:06:37,028
and I just pulled 
as hard as I could.

150
00:06:37,062 --> 00:06:39,030
And the lawnmower, like, 
roars to life.

151
00:06:39,064 --> 00:06:41,233
And I look up, and there's 
this whole line of guys

152
00:06:41,266 --> 00:06:42,868
and they're just looking at me

153
00:06:42,901 --> 00:06:45,237
with this shocked 
look on their face.

154
00:06:45,270 --> 00:06:46,938
And then I ran around 
the football field

155
00:06:46,972 --> 00:06:49,708
mowing the lawn, you know?

156
00:06:50,175 --> 00:06:52,177
[applauding]

157
00:06:52,777 --> 00:06:55,280
(Danielle Feinberg) 
I think role models 
are hugely important.

158
00:06:55,313 --> 00:06:56,982
You're not gonna imagine 
you can do something

159
00:06:57,015 --> 00:06:59,117
unless you see someone 
that you can connect with

160
00:06:59,150 --> 00:07:00,986
that's doing the same thing.

161
00:07:01,019 --> 00:07:02,320
When it's a woman doing that,

162
00:07:02,354 --> 00:07:03,989
it's easier to make 
that connection.

163
00:07:04,022 --> 00:07:05,323
At a certain point you realize,

164
00:07:05,357 --> 00:07:07,826
"Oh, I do actually 
know what I'm doing,

165
00:07:07,859 --> 00:07:09,227
"and I'm actually 
pretty good at this,

166
00:07:09,261 --> 00:07:11,263
and I belong in this room."

167
00:07:20,639 --> 00:07:22,240
Gloria Steinem says 
that women have always been

168
00:07:22,274 --> 00:07:23,875
an equal part of the past,

169
00:07:23,909 --> 00:07:25,377
just not an equal part 
of history,

170
00:07:25,410 --> 00:07:26,912
which is the case, of course,

171
00:07:26,945 --> 00:07:29,748
here in computer science 
and technology.

172
00:07:29,781 --> 00:07:31,216
Women were 
the pioneer programmers.

173
00:07:31,249 --> 00:07:32,751
They've been written 
out of history

174
00:07:32,784 --> 00:07:34,886
unfortunately in many cases,

175
00:07:34,920 --> 00:07:36,388
but they were the ones 
who first understood

176
00:07:36,421 --> 00:07:38,990
that instructing the machine 
was more important

177
00:07:39,024 --> 00:07:41,126
than the hardware 
of the machine.

178
00:07:42,727 --> 00:07:44,896
One of the first women 
pioneers in computing

179
00:07:44,930 --> 00:07:48,900
was Ada Lovelace, 
Lord Byron's daughter.

180
00:07:48,934 --> 00:07:52,370
(Nathan Ensmenger) 
She's often considered to be 
the first computer programmer.

181
00:07:52,404 --> 00:07:54,339
Very often we trace 
the history of computing

182
00:07:54,372 --> 00:07:56,107
back to a guy named 
Charles Babbage,

183
00:07:56,141 --> 00:07:59,811
who, in England in the 1820s, 
built some machines

184
00:07:59,844 --> 00:08:04,983
that look like 
a modern computer.

185
00:08:05,016 --> 00:08:07,986
Ada Lovelace 
was a mathematician

186
00:08:08,019 --> 00:08:10,855
who wrote a first 
and very important description

187
00:08:10,889 --> 00:08:13,959
of Babbage's 
analytical engine.

188
00:08:17,095 --> 00:08:19,364
(Walter Isaacson) 
She really envisioned 
how punch cards,

189
00:08:19,397 --> 00:08:21,366
which instructed 
the mechanical looms

190
00:08:21,399 --> 00:08:23,969
that were driving 
industrial England,

191
00:08:24,002 --> 00:08:26,104
that they could be used by 
her friend Charles Babbage's

192
00:08:26,137 --> 00:08:28,840
difference 
and analytical engines

193
00:08:28,873 --> 00:08:30,942
so that they could do 
more than just numbers.

194
00:08:30,976 --> 00:08:32,077
They could be computers.

195
00:08:32,110 --> 00:08:35,313
They could do words and pictures and music and patterns.

196
00:08:37,849 --> 00:08:40,885
The first computers were built for special purposes:

197
00:08:40,919 --> 00:08:42,921
breaking the German 
wartime codes,

198
00:08:42,954 --> 00:08:44,756
calculating 
a missile trajectory.

199
00:08:44,789 --> 00:08:47,425
And if you wanted to reprogram 
them to do another problem,

200
00:08:47,459 --> 00:08:50,829
you had to unplug some cables 
and do some switches.

201
00:08:50,862 --> 00:08:52,864
And the women were in charge of doing the plugging

202
00:08:52,897 --> 00:08:54,332
and unplugging of the cables.

203
00:08:54,366 --> 00:08:57,035
They'd look at the diagram of the computer and figure out,

204
00:08:57,068 --> 00:09:00,338
"How would we move 
the cables to reprogram it?"

205
00:09:00,372 --> 00:09:02,407
It did not seem like 
the most important work,

206
00:09:02,440 --> 00:09:06,144
but it took a good 
mathematical mind.

207
00:09:06,177 --> 00:09:09,314
(Nathan Ensmenger) The designers thought that this would be an easy job,

208
00:09:09,347 --> 00:09:11,216
that the building 
of the machine

209
00:09:11,249 --> 00:09:13,018
would be 
the most difficult task.

210
00:09:13,051 --> 00:09:14,352
And then you 
would have a scientist

211
00:09:14,386 --> 00:09:15,920
who would define the problem

212
00:09:15,954 --> 00:09:18,123
and these women 
would just be coding it.

213
00:09:18,156 --> 00:09:20,358
They'd be translating it 
from human language

214
00:09:20,392 --> 00:09:23,728
into machine language.

215
00:09:23,762 --> 00:09:26,798
It turns out that coding 
was quite difficult.

216
00:09:26,831 --> 00:09:28,767
And so, these women played 
a very active role

217
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:32,904
in defining what 
a computer could do.

218
00:09:32,937 --> 00:09:34,906
They had this equipment 
and somebody had to figure out

219
00:09:34,939 --> 00:09:36,241
what to do with it.

220
00:09:36,274 --> 00:09:38,476
Well, that's always 
a good job to give to the women.

221
00:09:38,510 --> 00:09:40,211
Ha ha!

222
00:09:40,245 --> 00:09:42,814
Do something with this! 
Make it work.

223
00:09:42,847 --> 00:09:46,184
And, you know, in the early days 
of hardware and software,

224
00:09:46,217 --> 00:09:47,986
that was kind of 
what it was like.

225
00:09:48,019 --> 00:09:50,388
Hardware would put stuff 
as much as they could with it

226
00:09:50,422 --> 00:09:51,956
and they'd give it 
to software people.

227
00:09:51,990 --> 00:09:53,425
Do something with it.

228
00:10:00,932 --> 00:10:03,034
(Tracy Chou) 
I don't think software 
engineering, as an industry,

229
00:10:03,068 --> 00:10:04,235
is a meritocracy.

230
00:10:04,269 --> 00:10:08,406
I think it's a great ideal that 
engineering holds itself to,

231
00:10:08,440 --> 00:10:11,409
but it's very far 
from being that.

232
00:10:11,443 --> 00:10:14,412
I'm really excited that there is a lot more conversation around

233
00:10:14,446 --> 00:10:17,248
diversity in engineering 
and diversity in tech now

234
00:10:17,282 --> 00:10:19,117
than even there was 
a couple of years ago,

235
00:10:19,150 --> 00:10:21,386
'cause I think the first step 
is that awareness.

236
00:10:21,419 --> 00:10:31,930
♪♪♪

237
00:10:31,963 --> 00:10:34,799
I went to a conference 
in October 2013,

238
00:10:34,833 --> 00:10:37,302
and in there listening 
to a few people

239
00:10:37,335 --> 00:10:40,138
speaking about 
the lack of women,

240
00:10:40,171 --> 00:10:42,373
how bad the numbers were, how the numbers were declining.

241
00:10:42,407 --> 00:10:45,310
But nobody was talking about the actual numbers that they had

242
00:10:45,343 --> 00:10:47,946
or whether any of these tactics that they were deploying

243
00:10:47,979 --> 00:10:51,349
were helping with the numbers.

244
00:10:51,382 --> 00:10:53,318
And so, when I came back 
from the conference,

245
00:10:53,351 --> 00:10:56,821
I issued this call to action 
that people could count up

246
00:10:56,855 --> 00:10:58,289
the number of female 
software engineers

247
00:10:58,323 --> 00:10:59,491
as well as total 
software engineers

248
00:10:59,524 --> 00:11:02,527
within their companies 
and submit it to this project

249
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:05,864
and we could aggregate it 
into one place.

250
00:11:09,267 --> 00:11:11,336
Before it was more or less 
an open secret

251
00:11:11,369 --> 00:11:13,138
that diversity was 
a problem within tech,

252
00:11:13,171 --> 00:11:16,941
but when companies started 
putting these numbers out there

253
00:11:16,975 --> 00:11:19,077
with full diversity 
disclosure reports,

254
00:11:19,110 --> 00:11:21,279
it became very obvious for 
people outside the industry

255
00:11:21,312 --> 00:11:23,882
to look at those and say, "Wow, there really is a problem.

256
00:11:23,915 --> 00:11:25,617
"This is something 
we need to be focusing on

257
00:11:25,650 --> 00:11:27,919
and trying to address."

258
00:11:27,952 --> 00:11:37,996
♪♪♪

259
00:11:37,996 --> 00:11:42,934
♪♪♪

260
00:11:42,967 --> 00:11:50,074
♪♪♪

261
00:11:50,108 --> 00:11:51,409
(Jocelyn Goldfein) 
It's not a pretty picture.

262
00:11:51,442 --> 00:11:52,977
If you look at 
the different paths

263
00:11:53,011 --> 00:11:54,379
that computer scientists take,

264
00:11:54,412 --> 00:11:56,281
essentially 
the proportion of women

265
00:11:56,314 --> 00:11:59,083
just successively shrinks 
at every stage.

266
00:11:59,117 --> 00:12:00,251
So, however few CS majors,

267
00:12:00,285 --> 00:12:02,453
there are there are even 
fewer software engineers.

268
00:12:02,487 --> 00:12:06,057
There become even fewer very senior software engineers,

269
00:12:06,090 --> 00:12:09,861
even fewer founders 
of companies.

270
00:12:10,195 --> 00:12:12,230
We have got to 
figure out a way

271
00:12:12,263 --> 00:12:16,000
to make the pipeline 
of tech talent more robust.

272
00:12:16,034 --> 00:12:17,502
And in order to do that,

273
00:12:17,535 --> 00:12:21,005
we have to look at communities 
that, until this point,

274
00:12:21,039 --> 00:12:24,676
have really been 
overlooked and underutilized.

275
00:12:24,709 --> 00:12:25,944
This means that 
we have to ensure

276
00:12:25,977 --> 00:12:29,647
that people of color are part 
of this tech talent pipeline.

277
00:12:29,681 --> 00:12:31,516
We have to ensure 
that women and girls

278
00:12:31,549 --> 00:12:33,651
are part of this 
tech talent pipeline.

279
00:12:33,685 --> 00:12:36,454
We have to ensure that 
we're looking in all corners

280
00:12:36,487 --> 00:12:38,223
and crannies of the nation

281
00:12:38,256 --> 00:12:41,559
to make sure that we're reaching 
people who have the talent,

282
00:12:41,593 --> 00:12:45,663
need the skill, need the context 
for being able to succeed.

283
00:12:45,697 --> 00:12:57,008
♪♪♪

284
00:13:05,183 --> 00:13:06,517
I fight like a girl.

285
00:13:07,986 --> 00:13:10,188
(Aliya Rahman) 
I don't believe coding 
can be the great equalizer

286
00:13:10,221 --> 00:13:12,357
because there are so many things that we have to fix,

287
00:13:12,390 --> 00:13:16,394
but it is a medium 
towards equality.

288
00:13:17,495 --> 00:13:20,698
Good morning! 
How you doin'?

289
00:13:20,732 --> 00:13:23,067
(Aliya Rahman) 
We believe that the 
reason that there's a gap

290
00:13:23,101 --> 00:13:25,503
is actually related to some 
really real structural factors.

291
00:13:25,536 --> 00:13:27,205
Part of that is 
people's ability to, like,

292
00:13:27,238 --> 00:13:29,307
step away from their life to, 
like, learn this skill.

293
00:13:29,340 --> 00:13:36,581
♪♪♪

294
00:13:36,614 --> 00:13:39,083
We had 425 applications.

295
00:13:39,117 --> 00:13:40,585
We asked folks 
to talk in that application

296
00:13:40,618 --> 00:13:43,187
about how they saw themselves 
as part of a community

297
00:13:43,221 --> 00:13:45,556
that was underrepresented 
in the tech movement,

298
00:13:45,590 --> 00:13:47,425
and then talk about 
how they would use apps

299
00:13:47,458 --> 00:13:50,428
to improve the condition 
of those communities.

300
00:13:51,029 --> 00:13:54,399
So, all of them are people 
of color, 9 of 12 are women.

301
00:13:54,432 --> 00:13:55,733
We have someone 
from a reservation.

302
00:13:55,767 --> 00:13:57,635
We've got folks who are LGBT.

303
00:13:57,669 --> 00:13:59,504
And most of them 
did not go to college.

304
00:13:59,537 --> 00:14:01,205
(Aliya Rahman, teaching) 
All right so, welcome back.

305
00:14:01,239 --> 00:14:03,441
We had a big week 
last week, right?

306
00:14:03,474 --> 00:14:04,709
Fun stuff.

307
00:14:04,742 --> 00:14:06,644
(Aliya Rahman) 
I actually worked 
in social justice work,

308
00:14:06,678 --> 00:14:07,879
and community organizing,

309
00:14:07,912 --> 00:14:11,249
and activism for a lot of years, 
and one of the things I found

310
00:14:11,282 --> 00:14:14,485
is that I kept hiring 
really smart women,

311
00:14:14,519 --> 00:14:16,020
people of color, et cetera,

312
00:14:16,054 --> 00:14:17,655
to the same kind of 
low-level jobs,

313
00:14:17,689 --> 00:14:20,425
when really, they had 
fantastic ideas about tech

314
00:14:20,458 --> 00:14:23,094
and how we could do what 
we were doing much better.

315
00:14:23,127 --> 00:14:25,596
I built a lot of our own 
software and tech on the fly

316
00:14:25,630 --> 00:14:26,764
just 'cause I had 
a programming background.

317
00:14:26,798 --> 00:14:29,534
And I thought we should do something about that situation,

318
00:14:29,567 --> 00:14:31,536
and that the folks 
that all this kind of work

319
00:14:31,569 --> 00:14:33,071
is trying to reach out to,

320
00:14:33,104 --> 00:14:34,405
the communities 
it's trying to impact,

321
00:14:34,439 --> 00:14:35,807
those people 
should be the people

322
00:14:35,840 --> 00:14:37,508
who are making decisions, 
and making tools,

323
00:14:37,542 --> 00:14:39,744
and being part 
of the actual design,

324
00:14:39,777 --> 00:14:43,281
rather than just the users 
and consumers of technology.

325
00:14:43,314 --> 00:14:47,385
Code is mobility, and you know, racial minority groups,

326
00:14:47,418 --> 00:14:49,554
women, poor folks, 
have always fought

327
00:14:49,587 --> 00:14:53,091
to have access to those 
conduits towards power.

328
00:14:56,194 --> 00:14:58,830
(male news anchor) 
Tonight, 
the Crimson Controversy,

329
00:14:58,863 --> 00:15:02,233
seeing red at 
Harvard University.

330
00:15:03,201 --> 00:15:05,737
(female reporter) 
On the most prestigious 
college campus in the country,

331
00:15:05,770 --> 00:15:07,505
Harvard President Larry Summers

332
00:15:07,538 --> 00:15:10,274
floated the idea that when 
it comes to math and science,

333
00:15:10,308 --> 00:15:12,610
there may be 
an innate difference

334
00:15:12,643 --> 00:15:14,545
between men and women.

335
00:15:14,579 --> 00:15:17,148
MIT biology professor, 
Nancy Hopkins,

336
00:15:17,181 --> 00:15:21,085
who studies genetics, was so offended she walked out.

337
00:15:21,119 --> 00:15:24,655
When you send this message 
that maybe it's in your genes,

338
00:15:24,689 --> 00:15:27,191
you're asking women 
to come to work every day

339
00:15:27,225 --> 00:15:29,594
and prove over 
and over and over,

340
00:15:29,627 --> 00:15:32,330
"Yes, I really am good enough 
to be here,"

341
00:15:32,363 --> 00:15:34,832
and that is exhausting.

342
00:15:34,866 --> 00:15:36,868
What is the problem though 
with the precise words

343
00:15:36,901 --> 00:15:38,803
that Dr. Summers used?

344
00:15:38,836 --> 00:15:41,272
Do you dispute the fact 
that innate differences

345
00:15:41,305 --> 00:15:43,574
may play a role in why women 
are underrepresented

346
00:15:43,608 --> 00:15:46,878
at top levels of math 
and science faculty?

347
00:15:46,911 --> 00:15:48,880
I think there's no question 
there are differences

348
00:15:48,913 --> 00:15:51,215
between women and men.

349
00:15:51,249 --> 00:15:54,252
But when we use 
the word "innate,"

350
00:15:54,285 --> 00:15:57,488
then we move 
into a different arena.

351
00:15:57,522 --> 00:16:01,726
I do find it interesting 
that in all sorts of fields,

352
00:16:01,759 --> 00:16:05,563
women are now more 
represented than in the past.

353
00:16:05,596 --> 00:16:09,467
Did we all of a sudden 
become innately more capable,

354
00:16:09,500 --> 00:16:12,336
or does this have to do 
with the circumstances?

355
00:16:12,370 --> 00:16:16,474
Does this have to do 
with plain old discrimination?

356
00:16:16,507 --> 00:16:28,352
♪♪♪

357
00:16:28,386 --> 00:16:30,388
In neuroscience, 
we have no reason to think

358
00:16:30,421 --> 00:16:33,558
that there's anything about 
a male brain or female brain

359
00:16:33,591 --> 00:16:36,260
that makes it different 
in terms of its potential.

360
00:16:36,294 --> 00:16:40,531
Now, that said, if an individual 
or a group of individuals

361
00:16:40,565 --> 00:16:42,400
is better at programming,

362
00:16:42,433 --> 00:16:45,770
then that has to be 
coming from the brain.

363
00:16:45,803 --> 00:16:47,939
The big mistake people make 
is assuming

364
00:16:47,972 --> 00:16:50,274
that if it's coming 
from the brain,

365
00:16:50,308 --> 00:16:52,643
then it somehow 
must be innate.

366
00:16:52,677 --> 00:16:55,913
Because we know from decades and decades of neuroscience research

367
00:16:55,947 --> 00:16:59,750
that the brain, both its 
function and even its structure,

368
00:16:59,784 --> 00:17:02,854
are powerfully influenced 
by experience.

369
00:17:02,887 --> 00:17:05,223
I don't believe 
that there's any difference

370
00:17:05,256 --> 00:17:06,891
between 
the male and female brain

371
00:17:06,924 --> 00:17:09,827
that would make one gender 
be more successful

372
00:17:09,861 --> 00:17:12,396
at programming than the other.

373
00:17:12,430 --> 00:17:17,635
If you start at the beginning 
with exactly the same IQ,

374
00:17:17,668 --> 00:17:20,338
male and female, 
they would end up,

375
00:17:20,371 --> 00:17:25,610
given the same schooling, 
with the same ability to code.

376
00:17:25,643 --> 00:17:27,678
(Jennifer Raymond) 
Boys and girls are treated 
differently from birth

377
00:17:27,712 --> 00:17:30,481
by their parents, by their 
teachers, by their peers.

378
00:17:30,515 --> 00:17:32,283
So, imagine, 
by the time you look

379
00:17:32,316 --> 00:17:33,751
at a bunch of college students,

380
00:17:33,784 --> 00:17:35,987
they've had not just weeks 
or hours of training,

381
00:17:36,020 --> 00:17:41,325
but 20 years of their brain 
being trained by experience.

382
00:17:41,359 --> 00:17:43,995
There will be differences 
in their brains.

383
00:17:44,028 --> 00:17:45,997
But what doesn't make sense 
is a lot of people

384
00:17:46,030 --> 00:17:47,198
then conclude that 
those differences somehow

385
00:17:47,231 --> 00:17:50,735
were genetically predetermined, 
when we know that experience

386
00:17:50,768 --> 00:17:52,770
can produce those changes.

387
00:17:53,571 --> 00:17:57,909
[children chattering]

388
00:17:57,942 --> 00:17:59,443
(Grechen Huebner) 
They see a game, right?

389
00:17:59,477 --> 00:18:01,546
They don't think, "Oh, I'm learning programming,"

390
00:18:01,579 --> 00:18:03,247
or "Oh, I'm learning how to code

391
00:18:03,281 --> 00:18:05,416
"and I'm gonna decide 
to play this game

392
00:18:05,449 --> 00:18:07,285
because 
I'm a girl or I'm a boy."

393
00:18:07,318 --> 00:18:08,619
They just see a fun game.

394
00:18:08,653 --> 00:18:21,699
♪♪♪

395
00:18:21,732 --> 00:18:24,502
The biggest hindrance for 
them to start learning logic

396
00:18:24,535 --> 00:18:25,870
and programming logic

397
00:18:25,903 --> 00:18:28,573
and to think computationally 
was the syntax.

398
00:18:28,606 --> 00:18:31,008
So, we removed 
the necessity of syntax.

399
00:18:31,042 --> 00:18:32,543
We added symbols.

400
00:18:32,577 --> 00:18:33,878
Everything is very abstract.

401
00:18:33,911 --> 00:18:35,880
And so, they didn't need 
to know how to read.

402
00:18:35,913 --> 00:18:37,081
They don't even 
need to speak English

403
00:18:37,114 --> 00:18:40,484
in order to start learning 
programming with Kodable.

404
00:18:40,518 --> 00:18:42,987
We need more girls, we need more women interested in programming,

405
00:18:43,020 --> 00:18:44,589
but we need more people

406
00:18:44,622 --> 00:18:46,357
interested in programming 
in general.

407
00:18:46,390 --> 00:18:49,026
We don't have enough. 
We don't have nearly enough.

408
00:18:49,060 --> 00:18:50,995
So, we wanted to make 
something that was fun

409
00:18:51,028 --> 00:18:53,030
whether you 
were a boy or a girl,

410
00:18:53,064 --> 00:18:56,334
something that would boost 
your interest in programming

411
00:18:56,367 --> 00:19:00,371
and give you the skills to be 
able to learn it later in life.

412
00:19:00,404 --> 00:19:06,477
♪♪♪

413
00:19:06,510 --> 00:19:08,879
All children are so talented 
and so creative.

414
00:19:08,913 --> 00:19:11,315
So, as these tools 
become less expensive,

415
00:19:11,349 --> 00:19:13,484
and more available, 
and more embedded in class,

416
00:19:13,517 --> 00:19:15,753
and more kids get exposed 
at earlier ages,

417
00:19:15,786 --> 00:19:18,556
they'll be able to make and 
affect the world around them.

418
00:19:18,589 --> 00:19:22,059
Computer science 
should be a requirement

419
00:19:22,093 --> 00:19:26,664
in all U.S. public schools, 
and charter schools,

420
00:19:26,697 --> 00:19:28,065
and private schools.

421
00:19:28,099 --> 00:19:31,702
But we're paying our 
tax dollars, and as an employer,

422
00:19:31,736 --> 00:19:35,773
I'm not getting what 
I need from U.S. public schools

423
00:19:35,806 --> 00:19:38,609
because computer science 
is not being taught.

424
00:19:38,643 --> 00:19:51,689
♪♪♪

425
00:19:51,722 --> 00:19:53,424
The biggest problem we have

426
00:19:53,457 --> 00:19:56,894
is equipping enough teachers 
of computer science.

427
00:19:56,927 --> 00:20:00,631
Because it has not 
been required or even present,

428
00:20:00,665 --> 00:20:02,433
we do not have enough teachers

429
00:20:02,466 --> 00:20:06,137
who are trained 
to teach the curriculum.

430
00:20:06,170 --> 00:20:12,743
♪♪♪

431
00:20:12,777 --> 00:20:16,113
Schools can be technology rich, 
but curriculum poor.

432
00:20:16,147 --> 00:20:20,584
And that what is really 
needed is the curriculum,

433
00:20:20,618 --> 00:20:23,688
and the teachers, 
and the opportunities

434
00:20:23,721 --> 00:20:27,692
to experiment and explore 
with the technology.

435
00:20:27,725 --> 00:20:31,162
Most students have 
no exposure to programming

436
00:20:31,195 --> 00:20:32,997
as a young person.

437
00:20:33,030 --> 00:20:35,533
And I think that 
if it was done well,

438
00:20:35,566 --> 00:20:38,102
and part of the curriculum, 
really creating technology,

439
00:20:38,135 --> 00:20:39,870
innovating, 
giving them the tools

440
00:20:39,904 --> 00:20:41,939
that they actually can create 
things that are meaningful

441
00:20:41,972 --> 00:20:43,507
and relevant to their lives,

442
00:20:43,541 --> 00:20:46,977
could have these 
other really positive effects.

443
00:20:47,011 --> 00:20:50,114
(Megan Smith) 
People think that 
it's a specific subject,

444
00:20:50,147 --> 00:20:51,749
when it's actually 
part of everything.

445
00:20:51,782 --> 00:20:53,150
It can be part of history.

446
00:20:53,184 --> 00:20:54,685
It can be part of English.

447
00:20:54,719 --> 00:20:57,455
It can be part 
of all of your subjects.

448
00:20:58,789 --> 00:21:01,692
Of course we wanna teach 
kids to read and to write,

449
00:21:01,726 --> 00:21:03,027
to express themselves,

450
00:21:03,060 --> 00:21:05,796
but we never let them 
express themselves

451
00:21:05,830 --> 00:21:07,698
in a mathematical, 
scientific way.

452
00:21:07,732 --> 00:21:09,567
So, they need to be able 
to make things.

453
00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:12,036
They need to be able to do innovation, engineering, coding.

454
00:21:12,069 --> 00:21:16,507
That's all part of expression 
in the technical realm.

455
00:21:23,848 --> 00:21:27,084
(Lauren) You see this game and then you just wonder, like,

456
00:21:27,118 --> 00:21:30,121
"Wow, how does 
someone make this?"

457
00:21:30,154 --> 00:21:32,723
Like, 
"Maybe I want to try that too."

458
00:21:32,757 --> 00:21:36,494
I like coding 
because instead of, like,

459
00:21:36,527 --> 00:21:40,664
us being consumers we 
could be like a producer of it.

460
00:21:40,698 --> 00:21:44,668
So, instead of us having to buy 
it, we could make our own game.

461
00:21:46,637 --> 00:21:49,540
(Kimberly Bryant) 
I think that all-girl events 
really give the girls

462
00:21:49,573 --> 00:21:51,876
an environment 
where they feel comfortable,

463
00:21:51,909 --> 00:21:54,812
they feel supported, and they 
can really just be themselves.

464
00:21:54,845 --> 00:21:56,680
You know, uniquely themselves,

465
00:21:56,714 --> 00:21:59,917
and really learn in this 
environment that's unencumbered

466
00:21:59,950 --> 00:22:03,220
by any stereotypes 
of what they can and can't do.

467
00:22:03,254 --> 00:22:05,823
And I think that's what 
really helps them to thrive.

468
00:22:07,725 --> 00:22:10,094
Maybe we can--so, we can 
break out into two groups,

469
00:22:10,127 --> 00:22:11,962
focus on those 
two problem statements,

470
00:22:11,996 --> 00:22:14,632
and start coming up 
with solutions.

471
00:22:14,665 --> 00:22:16,901
(Kimberly Bryant) 
Introducing girls 
to activities

472
00:22:16,934 --> 00:22:18,269
like being in a hackathon,

473
00:22:18,302 --> 00:22:21,038
which is something 
that's really endemic

474
00:22:21,071 --> 00:22:24,008
to the tech culture, 
and doing it in a way

475
00:22:24,041 --> 00:22:26,110
where they can--it's not 
just that they'll always

476
00:22:26,143 --> 00:22:28,179
hack with girls 
and only girls,

477
00:22:28,212 --> 00:22:31,515
but this really gives 
that seed of self-confidence.

478
00:22:31,549 --> 00:22:32,883
And that's what 
we're trying to do,

479
00:22:32,917 --> 00:22:35,953
slowly change the ratio 
and perception

480
00:22:35,986 --> 00:22:39,924
of what girls can do, 
and starting with themselves,

481
00:22:39,957 --> 00:22:41,959
so then they can go back 
into the broader culture

482
00:22:41,992 --> 00:22:44,161
and really make a difference.

483
00:22:46,330 --> 00:22:48,999
We believe in really 
starting early in the pipeline

484
00:22:49,033 --> 00:22:52,736
and staying with our girls until they get through high school,

485
00:22:52,770 --> 00:22:54,872
and then hopefully decide 
to go to college

486
00:22:54,905 --> 00:22:57,608
and major in some type 
of technical career.

487
00:22:59,310 --> 00:23:01,879
(Hanna Clark) I've been thinking about some things in software engineering.

488
00:23:01,912 --> 00:23:03,814
I also have 
a couple startup ideas

489
00:23:03,848 --> 00:23:05,149
floating around in my head.

490
00:23:05,182 --> 00:23:10,187
So, it'll all depend 
which one happens first.

491
00:23:10,221 --> 00:23:13,157
(Lena Allston) 
Girls aren't really encouraged 
to pursue STEM careers,

492
00:23:13,190 --> 00:23:15,559
in computer science especially.

493
00:23:15,593 --> 00:23:17,294
A lot of times they're 
overlooked because, you know,

494
00:23:17,328 --> 00:23:19,063
it's the boys 
that are good at science

495
00:23:19,096 --> 00:23:22,633
and it's the boys that are 
taking apart computers at age 9.

496
00:23:22,666 --> 00:23:24,068
And so, girls are 
just not encouraged

497
00:23:24,101 --> 00:23:25,603
to do that kind of stuff,

498
00:23:25,636 --> 00:23:27,104
and they're kind of 
pushed to the side

499
00:23:27,137 --> 00:23:28,939
when it comes to 
the heavy duty tech.

500
00:23:28,973 --> 00:23:30,140
And I'm a perfect example of it.

501
00:23:30,174 --> 00:23:32,309
Like, I didn't even know 
what computer scientists did

502
00:23:32,343 --> 00:23:35,312
until my sophomore year 
of college.

503
00:23:35,346 --> 00:23:36,847
Having women in computer science

504
00:23:36,881 --> 00:23:39,283
and having African Americans 
in the industry,

505
00:23:39,316 --> 00:23:42,286
it just adds another layer 
of diversity.

506
00:23:42,319 --> 00:23:45,089
You know, diversity of thought, diversity of perspective.

507
00:23:45,122 --> 00:23:46,991
(Hanna Clark) 
We need a balance.

508
00:23:47,024 --> 00:23:48,626
Different people 
and different perspectives

509
00:23:48,659 --> 00:23:50,728
are gonna bring a balance 
and they're gonna result

510
00:23:50,761 --> 00:23:52,897
in things being 
more well-rounded.

511
00:23:52,930 --> 00:23:56,734
And otherwise, you may 
end up with one perspective

512
00:23:56,767 --> 00:24:00,704
and it's not going to be 
as beneficial to everybody.

513
00:24:12,716 --> 00:24:14,318
(female reporter) 
The U.S. transportation 
department announced

514
00:24:14,351 --> 00:24:16,020
new rules for airbags

515
00:24:16,053 --> 00:24:18,255
to eliminate deaths 
attributed to them.

516
00:24:18,289 --> 00:24:22,826
In about 160 cases, airbags 
have been blamed for death.

517
00:24:25,262 --> 00:24:27,264
(Ari Schlesinger) 
Unfortunately, 
the first round of airbags

518
00:24:27,298 --> 00:24:30,367
killed a lot 
of women and children,

519
00:24:30,401 --> 00:24:32,903
and it turns out 
that the airbags were developed

520
00:24:32,937 --> 00:24:36,040
for the average specs 
of the engineer on the team,

521
00:24:36,073 --> 00:24:39,276
and those engineers 
happened to all be white men.

522
00:24:39,310 --> 00:24:43,414
And so, airbags were not 
developed with women in mind,

523
00:24:43,447 --> 00:24:47,918
and as a result, ended up 
killing a lot of people.

524
00:24:47,952 --> 00:24:52,089
And if you had had women on that team, you'd think that,

525
00:24:52,122 --> 00:24:55,726
"Hey, this airbag might kill me. I am not as tall as you are.

526
00:24:55,759 --> 00:24:57,294
I don't weigh 
as much as you do.

527
00:24:57,328 --> 00:24:58,963
My frame is not the same,"

528
00:24:58,996 --> 00:25:01,165
that conversation 
would have happened.

529
00:25:03,434 --> 00:25:06,370
So, there's a long history 
across all sorts of fields

530
00:25:06,403 --> 00:25:11,942
that diversity is critically 
important if the innovations

531
00:25:11,976 --> 00:25:17,715
are going to positively 
impact all people.

532
00:25:17,748 --> 00:25:20,351
When the first voice recognition systems were designed,

533
00:25:20,384 --> 00:25:22,386
it was by men.

534
00:25:22,419 --> 00:25:25,723
They were using 
male voices to test it.

535
00:25:25,756 --> 00:25:29,259
And what ended up happening is 
that women could not be heard.

536
00:25:29,293 --> 00:25:31,295
Not only could 
women's voices not be heard,

537
00:25:31,328 --> 00:25:33,764
but then when they were 
doing voice recognition

538
00:25:33,797 --> 00:25:37,968
and video tracking, 
women could not be seen.

539
00:25:39,737 --> 00:25:43,173
(Roz Ho) 
Back in the late '90s, 
we were putting a feature

540
00:25:43,207 --> 00:25:45,009
in all of the Office products--

541
00:25:45,042 --> 00:25:47,077
Word, Excel, Power Point--

542
00:25:47,111 --> 00:25:49,213
that's called 
the Office Assistant.

543
00:25:49,246 --> 00:25:52,149
And it's an animated character 
that pops up

544
00:25:52,182 --> 00:25:55,986
and gives you help 
on what you're doing.

545
00:25:56,020 --> 00:25:58,322
We did a bunch 
of focus group testing

546
00:25:58,355 --> 00:26:01,825
and the results came back 
kind of negative.

547
00:26:01,859 --> 00:26:05,896
Most of the women thought 
the characters were too male.

548
00:26:05,929 --> 00:26:08,999
And that they were 
leering at them.

549
00:26:09,033 --> 00:26:10,734
So, we're sitting 
in a conference room.

550
00:26:10,768 --> 00:26:13,771
There's me and, I think, 
like 11 or 12 guys.

551
00:26:13,804 --> 00:26:15,973
And we're going through 
the results and they said,

552
00:26:16,006 --> 00:26:17,808
"I don't see it.

553
00:26:17,841 --> 00:26:19,877
I just don't know 
what they're talking about."

554
00:26:19,910 --> 00:26:21,812
I said, "Guys, guys, look.

555
00:26:21,845 --> 00:26:23,847
"I'm a woman 
and I'm gonna tell you

556
00:26:23,881 --> 00:26:27,284
"these animated characters 
are male-looking.

557
00:26:27,317 --> 00:26:31,255
"And you went and spent 
$100,000 on a focus group.

558
00:26:31,288 --> 00:26:32,956
"You went and asked 
all these people,

559
00:26:32,990 --> 00:26:36,427
and you're just going to discard all of this information?"

560
00:26:36,460 --> 00:26:39,229
So, we ended up shipping 
with ten male characters

561
00:26:39,263 --> 00:26:41,932
and two female characters.

562
00:26:41,965 --> 00:26:44,902
And I just thought 
that was so instructive

563
00:26:44,935 --> 00:26:48,806
because they were ready 
to toss away data

564
00:26:48,839 --> 00:26:51,809
because they couldn't 
see it for themselves.

565
00:26:52,276 --> 00:26:55,145
In computer science, 
an important mantra is,

566
00:26:55,179 --> 00:26:56,880
"You are not your user."

567
00:26:56,914 --> 00:26:58,449
There's a narrative in this

568
00:26:58,482 --> 00:27:00,284
"Women in computer 
science" story

569
00:27:00,317 --> 00:27:02,920
which is saying men 
are gonna make mistakes

570
00:27:02,953 --> 00:27:05,122
if they're designing for women,

571
00:27:05,155 --> 00:27:08,292
and that we need women if women 
are gonna be using the tools.

572
00:27:08,325 --> 00:27:11,328
And I think that that 
is letting people off easy.

573
00:27:11,361 --> 00:27:13,063
Women aren't this magical sauce

574
00:27:13,097 --> 00:27:14,398
that we're gonna 
sprinkle on everybody

575
00:27:14,431 --> 00:27:16,467
and they're gonna 
think about their users.

576
00:27:16,500 --> 00:27:18,969
Every developer, 
every person who's designing,

577
00:27:19,002 --> 00:27:20,504
needs to be thinking 
about their users.

578
00:27:21,171 --> 00:27:23,240
To be a programmer, 
you have to do two things.

579
00:27:23,273 --> 00:27:26,110
You have to be able to think 
logically, in an algorithm.

580
00:27:26,143 --> 00:27:27,511
Step one, step two, step three.

581
00:27:27,544 --> 00:27:29,847
Either/or, and/or.

582
00:27:29,880 --> 00:27:33,851
But you also have to be able 
to translate real world problems

583
00:27:33,884 --> 00:27:37,121
into a machine's language 
so you can say,

584
00:27:37,154 --> 00:27:39,056
"Here's what 
we're trying to solve

585
00:27:39,089 --> 00:27:40,991
and here are the steps 
to do it."

586
00:27:45,429 --> 00:27:48,098
(male instructor) 
The electromechanical 
differential analyzer

587
00:27:48,132 --> 00:27:51,268
performs scientific 
and industrial marvels.

588
00:27:51,301 --> 00:27:54,338
(Helen Bradley) 
Grace Hopper was the first 
person who came up with

589
00:27:54,371 --> 00:27:57,975
the concept of real programming languages and compilers.

590
00:27:58,008 --> 00:27:59,309
And what she enabled

591
00:27:59,343 --> 00:28:01,879
was computers 
to be used in business,

592
00:28:01,912 --> 00:28:04,848
'cause now you could write 
more complex programs.

593
00:28:07,117 --> 00:28:09,253
(male news anchor) 
Captain Hopper 
is a wiz at mathematics,

594
00:28:09,286 --> 00:28:11,088
some would say a genius,

595
00:28:11,121 --> 00:28:13,624
one of that small band 
of brothers and sisters

596
00:28:13,657 --> 00:28:15,893
who ushered in 
the computer revolution.

597
00:28:15,926 --> 00:28:19,563
And as far as we've progressed since this vacuum-tubed monster,

598
00:28:19,596 --> 00:28:23,467
Captain Hopper says, 
"We ain't seen nothin' yet."

599
00:28:23,500 --> 00:28:26,170
You talk a lot about 
the computer revolution.

600
00:28:26,203 --> 00:28:28,906
I thought, 
we're in it and it's over.

601
00:28:28,939 --> 00:28:30,240
No, we're only 
at the beginning.

602
00:28:30,274 --> 00:28:31,575
We've been through 
the preliminaries.

603
00:28:31,608 --> 00:28:33,110
(news anchor) 
Well what's it gonna be like?

604
00:28:33,143 --> 00:28:35,179
We've got the Model-T.

605
00:28:36,013 --> 00:28:38,148
Grace Hopper had 
a piss-and-vinegar personality.

606
00:28:38,182 --> 00:28:39,883
She was like 
a great Navy person.

607
00:28:39,917 --> 00:28:41,418
She could curse 
with the best of 'em,

608
00:28:41,451 --> 00:28:46,156
and she ran that crew as if 
she were a Navy commander.

609
00:28:48,192 --> 00:28:50,928
She stays in the Navy 
the rest of her career.

610
00:28:50,961 --> 00:28:53,297
In fact, they keep 
extending her retirement

611
00:28:53,330 --> 00:28:55,365
because she's writing 
programming languages

612
00:28:55,399 --> 00:28:58,035
for the Navy 
all the way through.

613
00:28:58,068 --> 00:29:01,104
People believe that she 
coined the term, "Bug,"

614
00:29:01,138 --> 00:29:05,042
because of a moth that 
was found in the vacuum tubes.

615
00:29:05,075 --> 00:29:06,376
So then, they kept saying

616
00:29:06,410 --> 00:29:09,213
that they would have 
a bug in a system.

617
00:29:09,246 --> 00:29:11,415
(Nathan Ensmenger) 
She was working 
on one of her early machines

618
00:29:11,448 --> 00:29:13,083
and found this moth.

619
00:29:13,116 --> 00:29:15,385
And in her lab notebooks 
from this period,

620
00:29:15,419 --> 00:29:18,589
we have this description 
of the very first computer bug

621
00:29:18,622 --> 00:29:23,193
and it's taped 
right into the notebook.

622
00:29:23,227 --> 00:29:24,428
And debugging, of course,

623
00:29:24,461 --> 00:29:26,697
is one of the things that's 
so hard about programming.

624
00:29:26,730 --> 00:29:28,665
It never quite works 
the first time around

625
00:29:28,699 --> 00:29:31,401
and the context 
is always changing.

626
00:29:31,435 --> 00:29:34,204
And so, she's not 
just giving it a language,

627
00:29:34,238 --> 00:29:37,374
she's also really defining 
what is important

628
00:29:37,407 --> 00:29:39,142
and what's intellectually 
challenging

629
00:29:39,176 --> 00:29:40,644
and stimulating 
about programming.

630
00:29:42,312 --> 00:29:44,715
(male instructor) 
When the first electronic 
computer was planned,

631
00:29:44,748 --> 00:29:47,050
it was estimated that there 
could never be a market

632
00:29:47,084 --> 00:29:50,120
for more than 2 or 3.

633
00:29:50,153 --> 00:29:54,324
Today, there are more 
than 5,000 computers.

634
00:29:55,626 --> 00:29:58,195
(Nathan Ensmenger) 
In the 1950s 
and the early 1960s,

635
00:29:58,228 --> 00:30:00,530
most estimates 
suggest at least 30%

636
00:30:00,564 --> 00:30:03,400
and as many as 50% 
of all programmers

637
00:30:03,433 --> 00:30:06,436
in this period 
would have been women.

638
00:30:06,470 --> 00:30:09,573
There's this wonderful article 
in the April 1967 issue

639
00:30:09,606 --> 00:30:11,475
of "Cosmopolitan Magazine."

640
00:30:11,508 --> 00:30:13,243
It's called 
"The Computer Girls,"

641
00:30:13,277 --> 00:30:16,980
and it's a description of the opportunities available to women

642
00:30:17,014 --> 00:30:19,249
in this computer industry.

643
00:30:19,283 --> 00:30:22,419
It's got quotes about style, 
and fashion, and dating,

644
00:30:22,452 --> 00:30:25,489
but it's this 
remarkably insightful piece

645
00:30:25,522 --> 00:30:28,759
on the fact that this is 
an industry open to women,

646
00:30:28,792 --> 00:30:32,062
that women 
are working in the industry,

647
00:30:32,095 --> 00:30:33,997
and that there are lots 
of opportunities for them

648
00:30:34,031 --> 00:30:36,333
to move forward.

649
00:30:37,234 --> 00:30:40,637
It's part of, I think, 
a confusing and conflicting

650
00:30:40,671 --> 00:30:44,374
set of messages 
that are beginning to emerge,

651
00:30:44,408 --> 00:30:47,511
however, about the role 
of women in computing.

652
00:30:47,544 --> 00:30:50,480
Companies like IBM are 
struggling to find programmers

653
00:30:50,514 --> 00:30:53,617
and they'll put an advertisement in the "New York Times"

654
00:30:53,650 --> 00:30:58,021
and say, "Are you the man to 
control the electronic giant?"

655
00:30:58,055 --> 00:31:01,491
It's encouraging programmers, I think, to think about themselves

656
00:31:01,525 --> 00:31:05,696
as a special breed, 
somebody with the right stuff.

657
00:31:05,729 --> 00:31:08,465
Women aren't disappearing 
from computing,

658
00:31:08,498 --> 00:31:10,767
but the kinds of stories we tell

659
00:31:10,801 --> 00:31:13,337
about who belongs 
in this industry

660
00:31:13,370 --> 00:31:16,039
are very much 
starting to be about men.

661
00:31:16,073 --> 00:31:18,742
If a girl has been told 
from the beginning that,

662
00:31:18,775 --> 00:31:21,812
"Oh, girls are good at art. 
Girls aren't good at science.

663
00:31:21,845 --> 00:31:25,716
Girls aren't good at math," 
then naturally this is just

664
00:31:25,749 --> 00:31:28,051
not a field they 
are going to concentrate on.

665
00:31:28,085 --> 00:31:31,488
And as they get older, they'll 
naturally start to fall behind.

666
00:31:31,521 --> 00:31:36,460
I think from a very young age 
girls and boys are kind of told

667
00:31:36,493 --> 00:31:38,295
what they're supposed to like.

668
00:31:38,328 --> 00:31:40,464
I've gone shopping in toy aisles

669
00:31:40,497 --> 00:31:43,333
and I'll see these pink 
and girly toys,

670
00:31:43,367 --> 00:31:45,535
and then I'll see these 
cool, like, trucks and trains,

671
00:31:45,569 --> 00:31:49,072
but they're obviously 
marketed towards boys.

672
00:31:49,106 --> 00:31:52,743
So, it's not that surprising 
to me that when girls get older

673
00:31:52,776 --> 00:31:56,646
they don't gravitate towards 
the maths and sciences.

674
00:31:56,680 --> 00:31:58,448
I played with anything.

675
00:31:58,482 --> 00:32:02,719
I played with G.I. Joes, 
I played with Legos,

676
00:32:02,753 --> 00:32:04,521
I played with Barbies.

677
00:32:05,288 --> 00:32:07,190
I love to shop, don't you?

678
00:32:07,224 --> 00:32:10,093
♪ I can't believe my ears, 
I can't believe my eyes ♪

679
00:32:10,127 --> 00:32:12,362
♪ Every Teen Talk Barbie 
is a different surprise! ♪♪

680
00:32:12,396 --> 00:32:13,697
Cool!

681
00:32:13,730 --> 00:32:15,232
(girl) 
What's she gonna say next?

682
00:32:15,265 --> 00:32:16,633
Do you like 
toasted marshmallows?

683
00:32:16,666 --> 00:32:19,202
(female reporter) 
That's the kind of talk 
we expect from Barbie,

684
00:32:19,236 --> 00:32:20,837
innocuous and upbeat.

685
00:32:20,871 --> 00:32:24,174
But here's the one-liner 
that got her into big trouble.

686
00:32:24,207 --> 00:32:26,343
Math class is tough.

687
00:32:26,376 --> 00:32:27,544
(reporter) 
Math class is tough?

688
00:32:27,577 --> 00:32:31,281
Mighty discouraging words 
from a female role model.

689
00:32:32,616 --> 00:32:34,151
(Helen Jane Hurren) 
"Hi guys," says Barbie.

690
00:32:34,184 --> 00:32:35,552
(reporter) 
Mom, Helen Jane Hurren,

691
00:32:35,585 --> 00:32:37,854
says she was excited 
to share the book,

692
00:32:37,888 --> 00:32:40,657
"Barbie: I Can Be 
a Computer Engineer,"

693
00:32:40,690 --> 00:32:45,395
with her two young girls, 
until she opened it up.

694
00:32:45,429 --> 00:32:46,897
We were shocked.

695
00:32:46,930 --> 00:32:50,200
(reporter) 
The book starts with Barbie 
designing a computer game,

696
00:32:50,233 --> 00:32:52,335
but she quickly 
gets into trouble,

697
00:32:52,369 --> 00:32:54,571
a virus crashing her laptop.

698
00:32:54,604 --> 00:32:57,274
Her solution, bring in the boys.

699
00:32:57,307 --> 00:33:00,644
"It will go faster if Brian 
and I help," says Steven.

700
00:33:00,677 --> 00:33:02,746
Barbie's reply? "Great!"

701
00:33:02,779 --> 00:33:06,850
The boys fix the problem, and 
after a high-five celebration,

702
00:33:06,883 --> 00:33:08,919
Barbie proudly proclaims,

703
00:33:08,952 --> 00:33:11,888
"I guess I can be 
a computer engineer!"

704
00:33:11,922 --> 00:33:14,691
Mattel is now apologizing 
for a children's book

705
00:33:14,724 --> 00:33:16,493
that is getting 
a lot of criticism.

706
00:33:16,526 --> 00:33:29,739
♪♪♪

707
00:33:29,773 --> 00:33:31,274
When I first started out,

708
00:33:31,308 --> 00:33:33,276
a lot of people in 
the toy industry told me

709
00:33:33,310 --> 00:33:36,279
that the concept of getting 
girls interested in engineering

710
00:33:36,313 --> 00:33:38,315
and computer science 
was very niche,

711
00:33:38,348 --> 00:33:39,716
that it would never 
go mainstream,

712
00:33:39,749 --> 00:33:44,387
that girls liked dolls 
and boys liked building.

713
00:33:44,421 --> 00:33:45,722
I didn't believe it 
for a second,

714
00:33:45,755 --> 00:33:48,258
but I needed 
to prove them wrong.

715
00:33:48,291 --> 00:33:50,861
Construction toys have 
been around for over 100 years,

716
00:33:50,894 --> 00:33:53,897
but for a long time they've 
really been kind of designed for

717
00:33:53,930 --> 00:33:55,165
and marketed to boys,

718
00:33:55,198 --> 00:33:58,535
which is unfortunate because 
they're really educational,

719
00:33:58,568 --> 00:34:01,204
and they help develop 
motor and spatial skills

720
00:34:01,238 --> 00:34:03,773
and problem solving.

721
00:34:03,807 --> 00:34:06,376
Young kids are so 
impressionable at that age,

722
00:34:06,409 --> 00:34:08,678
it's really important 
that we open up their minds

723
00:34:08,712 --> 00:34:09,846
to more options,

724
00:34:09,880 --> 00:34:12,716
especially girls who are 
inundated with princesses,

725
00:34:12,749 --> 00:34:15,685
and ponies, and pop stars.

726
00:34:15,719 --> 00:34:17,921
We've been thinking a lot 
about GoldieBlox as a way

727
00:34:17,954 --> 00:34:21,324
to get girls interested 
in engineering and technology

728
00:34:21,358 --> 00:34:22,759
through these characters.

729
00:34:22,792 --> 00:34:24,761
Because you need 
to have a role model, right?

730
00:34:24,794 --> 00:34:27,330
Somebody who you can 
look up to and wanna be like.

731
00:34:27,364 --> 00:34:39,276
♪♪♪

732
00:34:39,309 --> 00:34:41,945
♪ Come on, ditch your toys

733
00:34:41,978 --> 00:34:44,581
♪ Girls make some noise

734
00:34:44,614 --> 00:34:47,918
♪ More than pink, pink, pink

735
00:34:47,951 --> 00:34:50,487
♪ We want to think! ♪

736
00:34:50,520 --> 00:34:53,323
(Debbie Sterling) 
And I remember the moment when 
I watched the Super Bowl ad.

737
00:34:53,356 --> 00:34:55,425
It just brought 
tears to my eyes,

738
00:34:55,458 --> 00:34:58,562
watching that kind 
of horde of little girls

739
00:34:58,595 --> 00:35:00,597
racing down the streets 
with their pink toys

740
00:35:00,630 --> 00:35:02,532
and building a rocket ship.

741
00:35:02,566 --> 00:35:04,601
It was so incredibly empowering,

742
00:35:04,634 --> 00:35:08,772
particularly given the fact 
that typically in the Super Bowl

743
00:35:08,805 --> 00:35:12,542
you're seeing, you know, 
big boobs, and cars,

744
00:35:12,576 --> 00:35:16,613
and, you know, a lot of kind of 
typically sexist content.

745
00:35:16,646 --> 00:35:22,552
To see a girl empowerment ad, 
it was really disruptive.

746
00:35:25,889 --> 00:35:27,824
My mom was also 
a mathematician,

747
00:35:27,857 --> 00:35:29,993
and I grew up with the term 
"Stereotype threat"

748
00:35:30,026 --> 00:35:32,562
just, like, casually 
thrown around the household.

749
00:35:32,596 --> 00:35:34,497
But, like, there's some, like, 
pretty legitimate research

750
00:35:34,531 --> 00:35:36,833
showing that if you think you're 
gonna be less good at something,

751
00:35:36,866 --> 00:35:39,536
you'll start being 
less good at it.

752
00:35:39,569 --> 00:35:42,939
There are all kinds of forms 
of stereotype threat,

753
00:35:42,973 --> 00:35:44,674
'cause there's 
negative stereotypes

754
00:35:44,708 --> 00:35:46,943
about almost every 
single identity we have:

755
00:35:46,977 --> 00:35:49,579
our age, our race, 
our religion.

756
00:35:49,613 --> 00:35:52,515
But if you're, say, for example, 
a women trying to succeed

757
00:35:52,549 --> 00:35:58,054
in advanced computer science 
courses at an elite university,

758
00:35:58,088 --> 00:36:01,758
the prospect of being seen in 
terms of the negative stereotype

759
00:36:01,791 --> 00:36:05,462
about women's math ability 
can sort of knock you sideways.

760
00:36:05,495 --> 00:36:08,999
We got men and women who 
were very, very good at math,

761
00:36:09,032 --> 00:36:10,533
and we brought them 
into the laboratory

762
00:36:10,567 --> 00:36:12,969
and we gave them 
a very difficult math test

763
00:36:13,003 --> 00:36:15,839
that we knew 
would cause frustration.

764
00:36:15,872 --> 00:36:18,608
Our idea was that 
for these students,

765
00:36:18,642 --> 00:36:21,111
the situation would 
become different for men

766
00:36:21,144 --> 00:36:23,079
than it was for women.

767
00:36:23,113 --> 00:36:24,748
For men, they'd be 
frustrated and worried

768
00:36:24,781 --> 00:36:26,416
that they weren't 
performing as well

769
00:36:26,449 --> 00:36:28,018
as they might have 
anticipated.

770
00:36:28,051 --> 00:36:29,886
But for women, 
in addition to that,

771
00:36:29,919 --> 00:36:32,922
they might have worried that 
they may be confirming

772
00:36:32,956 --> 00:36:35,725
that alleged limitation 
in math ability

773
00:36:35,759 --> 00:36:39,462
that stereotypes in our society attribute to them.

774
00:36:39,496 --> 00:36:43,400
That extra worry would use up 
an extra amount of bandwidth

775
00:36:43,433 --> 00:36:46,736
as they fight with that, and 
resolve to push through that,

776
00:36:46,770 --> 00:36:50,473
and to disprove that, 
and all the things that we do.

777
00:36:50,507 --> 00:36:52,575
But women performed 
a full standard deviation

778
00:36:52,609 --> 00:36:54,978
worse than men on a test,

779
00:36:55,011 --> 00:36:57,580
even though we had carefully 
matched the men and women

780
00:36:57,614 --> 00:37:00,984
for having the same skill level when they began.

781
00:37:01,017 --> 00:37:03,987
We do the experiment over again, 
but this time we tell them,

782
00:37:04,020 --> 00:37:07,023
"Look, you may have heard that 
women don't do as well as men

783
00:37:07,057 --> 00:37:09,459
"on difficult standardized 
math tests,

784
00:37:09,492 --> 00:37:11,928
"but that's not true for 
the test you're taking today.

785
00:37:11,961 --> 00:37:14,464
"The test you're taking today, 
women always do as well as men.

786
00:37:14,497 --> 00:37:16,132
They always have, 
they always will."

787
00:37:16,166 --> 00:37:19,102
Under that simple instruction, 
women's math performance

788
00:37:19,135 --> 00:37:23,473
went up to match that 
of equally skilled men.

789
00:37:23,506 --> 00:37:25,742
Even though women 
may do well

790
00:37:25,775 --> 00:37:28,144
in many of these 
subjects in school,

791
00:37:28,178 --> 00:37:32,115
there's this idea that you 
have to be a genius

792
00:37:32,148 --> 00:37:38,154
or have a certain kind of mind 
to succeed in that as a field.

793
00:37:38,188 --> 00:37:39,989
Women who have this view,

794
00:37:40,023 --> 00:37:43,593
that it's only a fixed kind 
of person who belongs there,

795
00:37:43,626 --> 00:37:48,832
start feeling the stereotype 
more strongly.

796
00:37:48,865 --> 00:37:52,068
They don't choose a field 
that says it's sheer brainpower

797
00:37:52,102 --> 00:37:53,803
that can't be taught.

798
00:37:53,837 --> 00:37:55,505
Some people have it, some don't,

799
00:37:55,538 --> 00:38:01,511
because they know who the 
field thinks doesn't have it.

800
00:38:01,544 --> 00:38:04,714
After 87 minutes of very 
competitive play, we have a tie.

801
00:38:04,748 --> 00:38:07,684
In the event of a tie, we 
move into a sudden death round.

802
00:38:07,717 --> 00:38:09,652
Each team is given 
the opportunity

803
00:38:09,686 --> 00:38:12,088
to choose their opponent.

804
00:38:12,122 --> 00:38:13,857
North Shore, 
who do you select?

805
00:38:13,890 --> 00:38:16,159
- The girl, dude. 
- The girl.

806
00:38:16,192 --> 00:38:17,427
Contestant Kraft.

807
00:38:17,460 --> 00:38:21,030
(facilitator) 
From Marymount, 
Miss Carolyn Kraft.

808
00:38:23,833 --> 00:38:25,568
We pick the girl too.

809
00:38:25,935 --> 00:38:28,571
You're just a woman 
with a small brain,

810
00:38:28,605 --> 00:38:30,940
with a brain a third the size of us.

811
00:38:30,974 --> 00:38:32,776
It's science.

812
00:38:33,543 --> 00:38:44,053
♪♪♪

813
00:38:44,087 --> 00:38:45,955
(Kiara) 
Red is my favorite color,

814
00:38:45,989 --> 00:38:49,259
and then Ruby 
is the stuff I'm using.

815
00:38:49,292 --> 00:38:50,927
Ahh.

816
00:38:50,960 --> 00:38:52,262
Isn't that a cool photo?

817
00:38:52,295 --> 00:38:53,429
See all these?

818
00:38:53,463 --> 00:38:56,933
All this stuff, that's, like, 
what I'm doing in code.

819
00:38:56,966 --> 00:39:00,570
So, every time I click on it, 
that something, it changes.

820
00:39:00,603 --> 00:39:02,105
Did you have to 
type all of this?

821
00:39:02,138 --> 00:39:05,008
Yeah, most of it. 
So it's kind of--

822
00:39:05,041 --> 00:39:06,743
(Isabella) 
I would be willing 
to learn it.

823
00:39:06,776 --> 00:39:08,111
It sounds so interesting.

824
00:39:08,144 --> 00:39:11,281
In high school 
they'll introduce it to you?

825
00:39:11,314 --> 00:39:13,283
(Kiara) 
No, they don't even 
do it in high school.

826
00:39:13,316 --> 00:39:15,285
They do it in like 
your senior year or whatever,

827
00:39:15,318 --> 00:39:16,820
which is way too late.

828
00:39:16,853 --> 00:39:18,822
So, they don't--and so 
people are not interested in it.

829
00:39:18,855 --> 00:39:20,156
Yeah, and most people, like,

830
00:39:20,190 --> 00:39:22,025
who go to computer science 
in college,

831
00:39:22,058 --> 00:39:25,195
they've been coding and programming since they were 10.

832
00:39:25,228 --> 00:39:27,597
Like, full websites and things.

833
00:39:27,630 --> 00:39:31,568
(Sammie) 
I took this Java 
coding course at Berkeley

834
00:39:31,601 --> 00:39:33,203
and it was so intense.

835
00:39:33,236 --> 00:39:35,572
Like, it was supposed to 
be a beginner course

836
00:39:35,605 --> 00:39:37,774
and it was all, 
like, 16-year-old guys

837
00:39:37,807 --> 00:39:39,776
who had already-- 
who obviously already

838
00:39:39,809 --> 00:39:41,277
knew what they were doing.

839
00:39:41,311 --> 00:39:44,714
(Yuni) 
Were you intimidated because 
it was all, like, mostly male,

840
00:39:44,747 --> 00:39:48,017
or were you intimidated because of the level that they were at?

841
00:39:48,051 --> 00:39:50,887
(Sammie) Well, it was mostly the level they were at, plus I was like--

842
00:39:50,920 --> 00:39:53,256
I was, like, 
this 12-year-old little girl

843
00:39:53,289 --> 00:39:55,058
with all these older guys 
that had, like,

844
00:39:55,091 --> 00:39:58,027
no idea what I was doing.

845
00:39:58,061 --> 00:40:01,197
(Kiara) 
A lot of girls go into, 
like, college-level courses

846
00:40:01,231 --> 00:40:02,732
and they feel so behind.

847
00:40:02,765 --> 00:40:04,701
It's not that they're 
necessarily behind,

848
00:40:04,734 --> 00:40:06,169
it's just that they 
haven't been learning

849
00:40:06,202 --> 00:40:09,005
as long as some of the 
other students and boys.

850
00:40:09,038 --> 00:40:12,141
Also, like, computer scientists and software engineers,

851
00:40:12,175 --> 00:40:13,676
I think it's 
the most sought-after job

852
00:40:13,710 --> 00:40:15,011
in the world right now.

853
00:40:15,044 --> 00:40:16,779
And especially, they're also looking for, like,

854
00:40:16,813 --> 00:40:20,984
female coders and things, and 
they're, like, so hard to find.

855
00:40:21,017 --> 00:40:23,686
(Isabella) So, when did you decide you wanted to create a website?

856
00:40:23,720 --> 00:40:25,922
I've been thinking about 
doing this since I was about 11,

857
00:40:25,955 --> 00:40:30,727
but then I actually started 
doing this--it kind of, like--

858
00:40:30,760 --> 00:40:33,196
I think it was at 
the start of 8th grade.

859
00:40:33,229 --> 00:40:34,364
How did you get the idea?

860
00:40:34,397 --> 00:40:37,267
Well, my dad, because I am 
in at his work all the time

861
00:40:37,300 --> 00:40:38,835
and I see 
all these ninja coders.

862
00:40:38,868 --> 00:40:40,169
And they're so ninja.

863
00:40:40,203 --> 00:40:41,704
Inspired.

864
00:40:41,738 --> 00:40:43,039
Yeah, and they're not weird.

865
00:40:43,072 --> 00:40:44,741
Like, you can, like-- 
they'll talk to you.

866
00:40:44,774 --> 00:40:45,875
(Sammie) 
They're actual people?

867
00:40:45,909 --> 00:40:48,344
Yeah! And they, like, talk 
to you and I've had, like,

868
00:40:48,378 --> 00:40:49,946
some great conversations 
with some of them,

869
00:40:49,979 --> 00:40:51,281
like, totally normal.

870
00:40:51,314 --> 00:40:53,650
They're, like-- 
they don't all wear glasses.

871
00:40:53,683 --> 00:40:54,984
Like, they're totally normal.

872
00:40:55,018 --> 00:40:56,319
Not the stereotype.

873
00:40:56,352 --> 00:40:58,187
Yeah, and so I was like-- 
I was like,

874
00:40:58,221 --> 00:40:59,889
"Oh my God, 
these guys are so cool.

875
00:40:59,923 --> 00:41:01,224
I wanna be like them."

876
00:41:01,257 --> 00:41:02,759
And yeah, okay, 
they are mostly men.

877
00:41:02,792 --> 00:41:04,093
But I was like,

878
00:41:04,127 --> 00:41:06,296
"That's fine 'cause I can 
just be a queen ninja."

879
00:41:06,329 --> 00:41:18,775
♪♪♪

880
00:41:18,808 --> 00:41:22,045
I have a niece who 
was always great in math.

881
00:41:22,078 --> 00:41:25,148
Great in math all the way 
through elementary school,

882
00:41:25,181 --> 00:41:26,749
junior high school.

883
00:41:26,783 --> 00:41:28,251
And in high school, 
all of a sudden

884
00:41:28,284 --> 00:41:30,386
she's not good 
at math anymore.

885
00:41:30,420 --> 00:41:32,855
And it's much more 
around the,

886
00:41:32,889 --> 00:41:35,825
"She doesn't want to be 
seen as being the smart girl."

887
00:41:35,858 --> 00:41:38,895
She doesn't-- 
it's all of those pressures.

888
00:41:38,928 --> 00:41:40,997
They want to be the cute girl, 
the popular girl,

889
00:41:41,030 --> 00:41:42,231
not the nerdy girl.

890
00:41:42,265 --> 00:41:45,101
Oh, I never wanted to be the 
cute girl or the popular girl.

891
00:41:45,134 --> 00:41:46,936
A lot of girls 
do though, right?

892
00:41:46,970 --> 00:41:48,404
I know.

893
00:41:48,438 --> 00:41:50,707
Girls start to associate 
math and science

894
00:41:50,740 --> 00:41:52,775
as not being something 
they want to be

895
00:41:52,809 --> 00:41:54,110
associated being good at.

896
00:41:54,143 --> 00:41:55,979
They don't want to be 
thought bad at math,

897
00:41:56,012 --> 00:41:57,380
they just want to be average.

898
00:41:59,782 --> 00:42:02,852
Hey, I'm totally lost. 
Can you help me?

899
00:42:02,885 --> 00:42:04,721
(Cady voiceover) 
But I wasn't lost, 
I knew exactly

900
00:42:04,754 --> 00:42:06,055
what Ms. Norbury 
was talking about.

901
00:42:06,089 --> 00:42:08,825
It's a factorial, 
so you multiply each one by N.

902
00:42:08,858 --> 00:42:10,393
(Cady voiceover) 
Wrong.

903
00:42:10,426 --> 00:42:13,129
Is that the summation?

904
00:42:13,162 --> 00:42:14,964
Yeah, they're the same thing.

905
00:42:14,998 --> 00:42:17,000
(Cady voiceover) 
Wrong, he was so wrong.

906
00:42:17,033 --> 00:42:19,402
Thanks, I get it now.

907
00:42:19,435 --> 00:42:21,437
[bell ringing]

908
00:42:22,138 --> 00:42:23,973
(Danielle Feinberg) In school, there's a big difference between

909
00:42:24,007 --> 00:42:25,708
what a woman is going through

910
00:42:25,742 --> 00:42:27,043
and what a man 
is going through.

911
00:42:27,076 --> 00:42:29,078
Now, it's hopefully 
changed a little bit,

912
00:42:29,112 --> 00:42:30,713
but when I was in college,

913
00:42:30,747 --> 00:42:33,716
there were 5% to 10% women 
in my classes,

914
00:42:33,750 --> 00:42:35,451
especially my 
computer science classes.

915
00:42:35,485 --> 00:42:37,754
And what that meant 
was the guys

916
00:42:37,787 --> 00:42:39,489
actually all teamed up 
on the homework.

917
00:42:39,522 --> 00:42:42,025
We'd all be in the same room, 
they'd be working on it,

918
00:42:42,058 --> 00:42:43,259
figure out the little, 
sort of, tricks

919
00:42:43,292 --> 00:42:46,262
that were embedded in everything 
and share it with each other.

920
00:42:46,295 --> 00:42:49,499
And they wouldn't 
even talk to me.

921
00:42:49,532 --> 00:42:51,200
I mean, I couldn't 
really do anything else.

922
00:42:51,234 --> 00:42:53,369
I loved it so much, 
I wasn't gonna give it up.

923
00:42:53,403 --> 00:42:56,072
But there was definitely-- 
it was a pretty hard path.

924
00:42:56,239 --> 00:42:58,041
I went to MIT.

925
00:42:58,074 --> 00:43:02,145
There really weren't too many 
people in my class freshman year

926
00:43:02,178 --> 00:43:05,948
who were that interested 
in computers, boys or girls.

927
00:43:05,982 --> 00:43:07,483
So, it was kind of unusual

928
00:43:07,517 --> 00:43:10,153
to be taking the first 
computer class for anyone.

929
00:43:10,186 --> 00:43:14,824
That class probably had 
one girl in it, which was me.

930
00:43:14,857 --> 00:43:18,895
And the next class, oh, 
it increased a lot by then.

931
00:43:18,928 --> 00:43:21,397
We had two women in it.

932
00:43:21,431 --> 00:43:24,067
I was told by many professors

933
00:43:24,100 --> 00:43:26,436
that I would never 
make it in industry

934
00:43:26,469 --> 00:43:30,139
and a woman should just as well go home and have babies.

935
00:43:30,173 --> 00:43:32,108
I was really wasting my time.

936
00:43:32,141 --> 00:43:34,110
I was lectured in a math class,

937
00:43:34,143 --> 00:43:36,813
singled out 
for having done my homework

938
00:43:36,846 --> 00:43:39,082
and lectured 
that women are inferior

939
00:43:39,115 --> 00:43:42,251
because they always 
do what they're told.

940
00:43:42,285 --> 00:43:45,188
That's not terribly pleasant 
when you're 18.

941
00:43:45,221 --> 00:43:50,393
I was not aware or focused 
on my gender in high school.

942
00:43:50,426 --> 00:43:52,261
The top performers in 
my math and science classroom

943
00:43:52,295 --> 00:43:53,830
in high school were women.

944
00:43:53,863 --> 00:43:55,431
It didn't feel strange there.

945
00:43:55,465 --> 00:43:57,567
But then when I went to college, 
all of a sudden

946
00:43:57,600 --> 00:44:00,136
I was receiving these 
messages that it was strange

947
00:44:00,169 --> 00:44:02,939
that I was a woman 
interested in math and science,

948
00:44:02,972 --> 00:44:04,807
interested in computer science.

949
00:44:04,841 --> 00:44:07,543
"Colleen, you won't like 
majoring in computer science.

950
00:44:07,577 --> 00:44:09,078
"You won't like 
sitting in a basement

951
00:44:09,112 --> 00:44:11,347
coding until 
3 in the morning."

952
00:44:11,380 --> 00:44:15,218
It seemed like every adult 
in my life between the ages--

953
00:44:15,251 --> 00:44:19,489
when I was the age 18 to 22, 
was telling me that same thing.

954
00:44:19,522 --> 00:44:21,491
And it wasn't until 
I was a senior in college

955
00:44:21,524 --> 00:44:23,526
where I found out that 
that wasn't something

956
00:44:23,559 --> 00:44:26,395
that my male colleagues 
were being told.

957
00:44:26,429 --> 00:44:29,432
There started to be an 
increase of the number of women

958
00:44:29,465 --> 00:44:31,434
who were studying 
computer science,

959
00:44:31,467 --> 00:44:36,205
and in the mid '80s 
it peaked around 40%.

960
00:44:36,239 --> 00:44:39,575
And I thought when I entered 
college around that time

961
00:44:39,609 --> 00:44:42,378
that we were, you know, 
on our way to being 50/50,

962
00:44:42,411 --> 00:44:44,947
because it was, you know, 
steadily going up.

963
00:44:44,981 --> 00:44:48,885
It's odd that we could have 
gotten close to gender parity

964
00:44:48,918 --> 00:44:52,221
in people studying 
computer science in the '80s

965
00:44:52,255 --> 00:44:54,590
and then have it 
decline from there.

966
00:44:54,624 --> 00:44:59,362
It's when the idea of the 
nerd genius came to the fore,

967
00:44:59,395 --> 00:45:03,266
and that's exactly when 
women started declining

968
00:45:03,299 --> 00:45:05,067
in their representation.

969
00:45:05,101 --> 00:45:07,937
This whole image formed of,

970
00:45:07,970 --> 00:45:13,042
"Do you have the right stuff 
to be a coder?

971
00:45:13,075 --> 00:45:16,279
A computer programmer? 
A computer geek?"

972
00:45:16,312 --> 00:45:18,948
And what this does 
is create this kind of culture

973
00:45:18,981 --> 00:45:22,385
of computing that today 
we know as computer hacking.

974
00:45:22,418 --> 00:45:25,521
In the '70s it was called--they 
were called the computer bums.

975
00:45:25,555 --> 00:45:29,258
They would hang around 
