that we're kind of building, 
like, a little mafia here of,

1451
01:06:59,547 --> 01:07:02,484
like, women in code 
and women in computer science.

1452
01:07:04,352 --> 01:07:06,454
(interviewer) 
So, why do you think 
there aren't more

1453
01:07:06,488 --> 01:07:08,690
women computer scientists?

1454
01:07:08,723 --> 01:07:10,458
That's a really good question,

1455
01:07:10,492 --> 01:07:15,497
and I would love to know the 
answer when you guys find out.

1456
01:07:15,530 --> 01:07:18,466
I'm the kind of person that, when I like something, I do it.

1457
01:07:18,500 --> 01:07:19,601
I went to MIT.

1458
01:07:19,634 --> 01:07:22,203
I did not think I was 
gonna be in computer science.

1459
01:07:22,237 --> 01:07:24,539
You know, I was the kind of girl 
that didn't really know

1460
01:07:24,572 --> 01:07:25,874
how to work her DVD player.

1461
01:07:25,907 --> 01:07:27,408
And so I was like, you know,

1462
01:07:27,442 --> 01:07:28,743
"I could never be 
a software engineer."

1463
01:07:28,776 --> 01:07:30,044
And I had to take a class

1464
01:07:30,078 --> 01:07:33,581
that was just kind of a basic 
Java for engineering class,

1465
01:07:33,615 --> 01:07:35,617
and I really liked it 
so I ended up switching

1466
01:07:35,650 --> 01:07:37,485
to a Math/CS major.

1467
01:07:37,519 --> 01:07:46,828
♪♪♪

1468
01:07:46,861 --> 01:07:48,363
I think people 
are sometimes surprised

1469
01:07:48,396 --> 01:07:50,498
when I tell them I work 
in computer science,

1470
01:07:50,532 --> 01:07:53,935
just because it is 
a male-dominated industry.

1471
01:07:53,968 --> 01:07:55,770
We're all first and foremost 
athletes here,

1472
01:07:55,803 --> 01:07:57,472
and I feel like I fit right in

1473
01:07:57,505 --> 01:08:00,008
'cause I've been a runner 
since I was born.

1474
01:08:00,041 --> 01:08:02,644
I can relate to people who 
understand that being active

1475
01:08:02,677 --> 01:08:04,679
is an important 
part of your life

1476
01:08:04,712 --> 01:08:06,414
and that it's okay to go out

1477
01:08:06,447 --> 01:08:08,750
and take an hour to run 
during the middle of the day,

1478
01:08:08,783 --> 01:08:10,285
'cause it means 
that you're gonna be

1479
01:08:10,318 --> 01:08:12,854
that much more productive 
when you come back.

1480
01:08:12,887 --> 01:08:15,323
The computer science culture 
that I experience

1481
01:08:15,356 --> 01:08:16,524
is what I get down here,

1482
01:08:16,558 --> 01:08:18,660
and I think that's probably 
different from what you get

1483
01:08:18,693 --> 01:08:19,994
in a lot of places.

1484
01:08:20,028 --> 01:08:22,030
That's the argument 
from the tooth.

1485
01:08:22,063 --> 01:08:24,832
It seems pretty easy.

1486
01:08:24,866 --> 01:08:26,367
(Evelyn Cordner) 
We all work on teams.

1487
01:08:26,401 --> 01:08:28,303
We all contribute 
to code equally.

1488
01:08:28,336 --> 01:08:30,572
So, it's very rare 
that you find yourself

1489
01:08:30,605 --> 01:08:33,408
working with a code base 
all by yourself.

1490
01:08:33,441 --> 01:08:37,545
The APIN point, 
when we load the profile?

1491
01:08:37,579 --> 01:08:39,781
Computer science kind of 
lets you go into any industry.

1492
01:08:39,814 --> 01:08:41,416
I could work in nutrition.

1493
01:08:41,449 --> 01:08:43,284
I could work in environmental.

1494
01:08:43,318 --> 01:08:44,786
You know, 
I can do whatever I want

1495
01:08:44,819 --> 01:08:46,921
because there's 
so much demand

1496
01:08:46,955 --> 01:08:49,057
for software engineers 
out there.

1497
01:08:49,090 --> 01:08:51,859
It definitely takes 
a more technical mind,

1498
01:08:51,893 --> 01:08:53,728
but, you know, 
I think anyone can do anything

1499
01:08:53,761 --> 01:08:55,063
they set their mind to.

1500
01:08:55,096 --> 01:08:57,465
If they're determined, 
they'll do it.

1501
01:09:04,072 --> 01:09:06,641
If we wait for 
the next generation,

1502
01:09:06,674 --> 01:09:09,777
that's not generally been a very 
successful approach to change.

1503
01:09:09,811 --> 01:09:17,619
♪♪♪

1504
01:09:17,652 --> 01:09:20,388
It was only my second job 
in New York, and I was like,

1505
01:09:20,421 --> 01:09:22,690
"Wow, you know, there are so 
many different people here.

1506
01:09:22,724 --> 01:09:25,526
This whole company just feels 
so mixed and wonderful."

1507
01:09:25,560 --> 01:09:27,695
And then I went to 
the engineering, and I was like,

1508
01:09:27,729 --> 01:09:30,498
"Oh, it's all white guys again." 
Like, "Here we go again."

1509
01:09:30,531 --> 01:09:31,966
And we came up with this idea

1510
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:35,570
about how to try 
and encourage more women

1511
01:09:35,603 --> 01:09:37,639
to join that 
engineering department.

1512
01:09:37,672 --> 01:09:44,979
♪♪♪

1513
01:09:45,013 --> 01:09:46,648
The first initiative, 
as I understand it,

1514
01:09:46,681 --> 01:09:48,783
was supplying grants for women

1515
01:09:48,816 --> 01:09:50,785
to attend Hacker School 
for the summer.

1516
01:09:50,818 --> 01:09:53,488
Etsy started that 
in the summer of 2012,

1517
01:09:53,521 --> 01:09:55,556
and that was the batch 
that I attended.

1518
01:09:55,590 --> 01:09:58,693
From there, 
there was enormous growth

1519
01:09:58,726 --> 01:10:01,496
in the number of 
female engineers at Etsy.

1520
01:10:01,529 --> 01:10:09,103
♪♪♪

1521
01:10:09,137 --> 01:10:10,972
Our tech group 
is made up of 31% women.

1522
01:10:11,005 --> 01:10:13,574
I've seen a number of managers 
take steps to make sure

1523
01:10:13,608 --> 01:10:15,576
that our interview panels 
are super diverse

1524
01:10:15,610 --> 01:10:17,578
and that the female engineers 
we're interviewing

1525
01:10:17,612 --> 01:10:19,447
aren't just, like, 
the culture slot.

1526
01:10:19,480 --> 01:10:21,783
And also, we talk a lot about 
how we retain women here,

1527
01:10:21,816 --> 01:10:24,419
so we don't just focus on 
the pipeline problem.

1528
01:10:24,452 --> 01:10:25,753
I don't think 
it's that difficult

1529
01:10:25,787 --> 01:10:27,655
to hire more women coders.

1530
01:10:27,689 --> 01:10:28,990
I go to a lot of conferences.

1531
01:10:29,023 --> 01:10:30,525
I meet a lot of women.

1532
01:10:30,558 --> 01:10:31,859
They're all qualified, 
and they're all amazing,

1533
01:10:31,893 --> 01:10:35,129
and I want them all 
to come work for us.

1534
01:10:35,163 --> 01:10:36,931
Having more women here 
has made

1535
01:10:36,964 --> 01:10:38,666
the line for the bathroom 
a lot longer,

1536
01:10:38,700 --> 01:10:40,168
but I think that 
that's an okay difference

1537
01:10:40,201 --> 01:10:41,703
than other startups.

1538
01:10:41,736 --> 01:10:42,870
(Bethany Macri) 
I asked my male coworkers,

1539
01:10:42,904 --> 01:10:45,106
"What do you think of 
having females on the team?"

1540
01:10:45,139 --> 01:10:47,442
And they said, "We're happier."

1541
01:10:47,475 --> 01:10:49,711
They don't want to be a part 
of something that's backwards

1542
01:10:49,744 --> 01:10:53,748
and they don't want to not have 
the best people around them.

1543
01:10:53,781 --> 01:10:55,683
(Marc Hedlund) 
We acknowledged the problem.

1544
01:10:55,717 --> 01:10:57,819
We devoted, really, a lot 
of money, and resources,

1545
01:10:57,852 --> 01:11:01,022
and time to it, and we got 
a lot of very good responses

1546
01:11:01,055 --> 01:11:03,925
as a result of that.

1547
01:11:03,958 --> 01:11:06,461
I think what we did 
was good, but to me,

1548
01:11:06,494 --> 01:11:08,129
the next step is to say

1549
01:11:08,162 --> 01:11:10,565
real substantial change 
in the industry has to come

1550
01:11:10,598 --> 01:11:12,633
from there being women 
in leadership roles

1551
01:11:12,667 --> 01:11:14,035
in the industry.

1552
01:11:14,068 --> 01:11:16,471
You have to be impatient. 
This has to happen now.

1553
01:11:16,504 --> 01:11:17,972
We have to do 
what we can now.

1554
01:11:18,005 --> 01:11:19,707
Whatever it takes 
to move the number now,

1555
01:11:19,741 --> 01:11:21,075
we have to do that now.

1556
01:11:21,943 --> 01:11:24,846
(Tracy Chou) 
41% of women in tech

1557
01:11:24,879 --> 01:11:26,781
will leave by the 10-year mark

1558
01:11:26,814 --> 01:11:29,550
versus 17% for men.

1559
01:11:29,584 --> 01:11:31,052
A lot of women feel like, 
around mid-career,

1560
01:11:31,085 --> 01:11:34,789
that their career 
trajectories are slowing down

1561
01:11:34,822 --> 01:11:36,591
and their growth is stalling,

1562
01:11:36,624 --> 01:11:38,726
as opposed to many men who, 
around mid-career,

1563
01:11:38,760 --> 01:11:41,729
are starting to see 
their careers accelerate.

1564
01:11:41,763 --> 01:11:43,231
Yes, we do need 
to get more women

1565
01:11:43,264 --> 01:11:44,799
going through the pipeline.

1566
01:11:44,832 --> 01:11:46,601
And there is a lot to be done

1567
01:11:46,634 --> 01:11:48,236
in terms of keeping 
women in industry

1568
01:11:48,269 --> 01:11:50,204
once they're already there.

1569
01:11:50,238 --> 01:12:00,481
♪♪♪

1570
01:12:00,515 --> 01:12:03,851
We're on a path 
that's unstoppable,

1571
01:12:03,885 --> 01:12:05,853
and you guys 
and we, the techies,

1572
01:12:05,887 --> 01:12:07,622
are a big part of that.

1573
01:12:07,655 --> 01:12:09,957
One of the big things that we 
just have to keep doing

1574
01:12:09,991 --> 01:12:11,826
is keep demanding and pushing.

1575
01:12:11,859 --> 01:12:13,895
You know, that's how 
all change happens.

1576
01:12:13,928 --> 01:12:18,166
And we really have a 
culture problem in technology.

1577
01:12:18,199 --> 01:12:20,201
What I see is a death 
by a thousand cuts

1578
01:12:20,234 --> 01:12:22,937
from all the unconscious bias 
that lives around us.

1579
01:12:22,970 --> 01:12:25,072
And I'm hopeful because 
I think the tech industry

1580
01:12:25,106 --> 01:12:27,275
could move the fastest 
of all the industries.

1581
01:12:27,308 --> 01:12:29,977
That's how we roll 
and that's what we could do.

1582
01:12:30,011 --> 01:12:32,079
If we see the problem, 
we can debug it,

1583
01:12:32,113 --> 01:12:35,016
and I encourage us to do that.

1584
01:12:35,049 --> 01:12:38,786
(Walter Isaacson) 
For the digital revolution 
to truly be great

1585
01:12:38,820 --> 01:12:41,989
and to transform this world, 
it's gotta be inclusive.

1586
01:12:42,023 --> 01:12:44,659
It's gotta have women. 
It's gotta have people of color.

1587
01:12:44,692 --> 01:12:47,829
It can't just be for 
a certain set of people.

1588
01:12:47,862 --> 01:12:50,932
Most of the role models 
are now historical role models.

1589
01:12:50,965 --> 01:12:52,600
people like Grace Hopper.

1590
01:12:52,633 --> 01:12:57,605
We need more modern heroes, girls who code, who are famous,

1591
01:12:57,638 --> 01:13:01,008
who can hold their own 
in the hackathon world,

1592
01:13:01,042 --> 01:13:04,011
and we need to 
celebrate them more.

1593
01:13:04,045 --> 01:13:06,013
It's not gender parity 
for the sake of gender parity.

1594
01:13:06,047 --> 01:13:09,083
I truly believe that the lack 
of coding access for women

1595
01:13:09,116 --> 01:13:12,186
is the most important domestic 
issue of our country's time.

1596
01:13:13,354 --> 01:13:15,656
We have seen girls 
who have literally

1597
01:13:15,690 --> 01:13:17,725
lifted their families 
out of poverty

1598
01:13:17,758 --> 01:13:19,627
because they've gotten 
access to coding

1599
01:13:19,660 --> 01:13:21,796
and they're now making websites,

1600
01:13:21,829 --> 01:13:23,130
or being the first 
in their families

1601
01:13:23,164 --> 01:13:24,665
to get out 
of public housing

1602
01:13:24,699 --> 01:13:28,603
and getting a job at Twitter, 
or eBay, or Square.

1603
01:13:28,636 --> 01:13:29,937
And we've also seen girls

1604
01:13:29,971 --> 01:13:32,006
that come from the best private schools in America

1605
01:13:32,039 --> 01:13:34,775
that have no access 
to computer science

1606
01:13:34,809 --> 01:13:37,111
and who have 
fallen in love with this.

1607
01:13:37,144 --> 01:13:39,180
Companies like Facebook 
are in a real position

1608
01:13:39,213 --> 01:13:40,448
to change the perspective.

1609
01:13:40,481 --> 01:13:43,851
I think, you know, if I think 
of products that teenage girls

1610
01:13:43,885 --> 01:13:46,721
use and love, I hope 
Facebook's high on that list,

1611
01:13:46,754 --> 01:13:49,123
and I hope that they are 
inspired to think that Facebook

1612
01:13:49,156 --> 01:13:52,927
is the kind of thing that 
is made by people like them.

1613
01:13:52,960 --> 01:13:54,795
It's not just made 
by Mark Zuckerberg.

1614
01:13:54,829 --> 01:13:56,797
I guarantee you that the 
women engineers of Facebook

1615
01:13:56,831 --> 01:14:00,134
have contributed far more code 
to Facebook than Mark has.

1616
01:14:00,167 --> 01:14:02,603
There are many, 
many more of us.

1617
01:14:02,637 --> 01:14:04,939
I want girls to think of it 
as something that is made

1618
01:14:04,972 --> 01:14:06,908
by teams of men and women 
working together

1619
01:14:06,941 --> 01:14:09,744
that they can contribute to, 
that they can create.

1620
01:14:09,777 --> 01:14:11,612
The farther 
into the future we get,

1621
01:14:11,646 --> 01:14:13,748
the more things 
are gonna be based on code.

1622
01:14:13,781 --> 01:14:15,283
If you stick with code

1623
01:14:15,316 --> 01:14:17,685
and you find the 
other things that you like,

1624
01:14:17,718 --> 01:14:20,655
you can ride coding 
into that career.

1625
01:14:20,688 --> 01:14:22,690
It isn't that coding 
is a career;

1626
01:14:22,723 --> 01:14:24,959
it is a zillion careers.

1627
01:14:24,992 --> 01:14:27,361
Computer science is becoming 
mandatory in many countries.

1628
01:14:27,395 --> 01:14:30,097
We're working to get 
the U.S. to that point.

1629
01:14:30,131 --> 01:14:34,335
New Zealand, South Korea, 
Israel, Estonia, the UK.

1630
01:14:34,368 --> 01:14:36,671
Those are all countries who 
are teaching computer science

1631
01:14:36,704 --> 01:14:39,807
to every child in their country.

1632
01:14:39,840 --> 01:14:41,642
I actually think 
that this is an issue

1633
01:14:41,676 --> 01:14:44,211
where we can learn 
from other countries.

1634
01:14:44,245 --> 01:14:46,180
India's ahead of us. 
Nigeria's ahead of us.

1635
01:14:46,213 --> 01:14:48,215
Cambodia's ahead of us. 
Cuba's ahead of us.

1636
01:14:48,249 --> 01:14:50,885
Vietnam's ahead of us. 
China's ahead of us.

1637
01:14:50,918 --> 01:14:52,787
These countries get it,

1638
01:14:52,820 --> 01:14:56,090
and they are educating 
their women in these fields.

1639
01:14:56,123 --> 01:14:58,426
(Megan Smith) 
There's a bunch of countries 
who are ahead of us.

1640
01:14:58,459 --> 01:15:01,862
And we'll kind of run to catch 
up, and hopefully move fast.

